library(stats)

# Extract numeric variables for PCA
numeric_data <- morpho[, -6]  # Exclude the 'sport' variable

# Perform PCA
pca_result <- prcomp(numeric_data, scale = TRUE)  # Scale the variables to have unit variance

# Summary of PCA
summary(pca_result)
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2    PC3     PC4     PC5
## Standard deviation     1.6607 0.9747 0.7956 0.67541 0.45066
## Proportion of Variance 0.5516 0.1900 0.1266 0.09123 0.04062
## Cumulative Proportion  0.5516 0.7416 0.8681 0.95938 1.00000
# Percentage of variability accounted for by the first component
percentage_variance_pc1 <- (pca_result$sdev[1]^2 / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)) * 100
cat("Percentage of variability accounted for by the first component:", percentage_variance_pc1, "%\n")
## Percentage of variability accounted for by the first component: 55.15588 %
# Percentage of variability accounted for by the first two components
percentage_variance_pc2 <- sum(pca_result$sdev[1:2]^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2) * 100
cat("Percentage of variability accounted for by the first two components:", percentage_variance_pc2, "%\n")
## Percentage of variability accounted for by the first two components: 74.15563 %
# Scree plot
plot(1:length(pca_result$sdev), pca_result$sdev^2, type = "b", 
     xlab = "Principal Component", ylab = "Variance", 
     main = "Scree Plot")

# Loadings of variables on the first two principal components
loadings <- pca_result$rotation[, 1:2]

component2_interpretation <- loadings[, 2]

# Angle estimation from the biplot (in degrees)
angle_estimate <- 90  # The angle between the vectors appears close to 90 degrees, suggesting no correlation (close to 0)

# Compute the actual correlation between bhd and arm
correlation_actual <- cor(numeric_data$bhd, numeric_data$arm)

# Print the estimated angle and the actual correlation
cat("Estimated angle between bhd and arm vectors in the biplot (degrees):", angle_estimate, "\n")
## Estimated angle between bhd and arm vectors in the biplot (degrees): 90
cat("Actual correlation between bhd and arm variables:", correlation_actual, "\n")
## Actual correlation between bhd and arm variables: 0.3683856

The angle between variable vectors in a biplot visually represents the correlation between those variables.

  • Acute angles, approaching zero degrees, indicate a strong positive correlation. This signifies that high values of one variable tend to correspond with high values of the other, and vice versa.
  • Orthogonal angles, near 90 degrees, suggest no significant correlation. In this case, changes in one variable are not systematically associated with changes in the other.
  • Obtuse angles, approaching 180 degrees, depict a strong negative correlation. This implies that high values of one variable tend to coincide with low values of the other.

By comparing the estimated angle between two variables, such as bhd and arm, with their actual correlation coefficient, we can assess the accuracy of our visual interpretation from the biplot. A close correspondence between an estimated right angle and a correlation close to zero signifies a valid interpretation of the data.

# Calculate MSE for linear regression on training data
mse_train_linear <- mean((train_data$mpg - train_data$mpg_pred_linear)^2)

# Calculate MSE for loess on training data

# Predict mpg using linear regression and loess on test data
test_data$mpg_pred_linear <- predict(f1, newdata = test_data)
test_data$mpg_pred_loess <- predict(f2, newdata = test_data)

# Calculate MSE for linear regression on test data

# Calculate MSE for loess on test data
